      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Now, I need to start gathering system information. I'll use bash to run PowerShell commands. Let's first check if there are any crash dumps in the typical locations (e.g., C:\\Windows\\Minidump). I'll also check event logs for critical errors.\n\nI'll run multiple commands in parallel. Let's start with:\n\n1. List minidump files.\n2. Check system information.\n3. Get recent event logs for system errors.\n\nI'll use PowerShell commands via bash. Since I'm in a Windows environment, I need to be careful with command syntax. I'll use `powershell -Command` or just run PowerShell commands directly via bash? Actually, the bash tool runs Windows PowerShell (5.1) commands, so I can just write PowerShell commands.\n\nLet's do this:",
      "timestamp": 1783146308328
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "bash",
      "code": "{\"command\": \"Get-ChildItem -Path \\\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\Minidump\\\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object -First 10\", \"description\": \"List minidump files in Windows Minidump folder\"}",
      "output": "(no output)",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783146310142
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "bash",
      "code": "{\"command\": \"Get-WinEvent -LogName System -MaxEvents 50 | Where-Object {$_.LevelDisplayName -eq \\\"Critical\\\" -or $_.LevelDisplayName -eq \\\"Error\\\"} | Select-Object -First 10 TimeCreated, Id, Message\", \"description\": \"Get recent critical/error system events\"}",
      "output": "(no output)",
